  The key design decision that makes your hardware enough

  Your 2GB GPU is too small to matter — modern local LLM runners need ~3GB+ VRAM
  even for small quantized models, so plan for CPU-only inference. That sounds
  bad, but it's fine because of one architectural choice:

  Don't ask the LLM to detect anything. Your Isolation Forest already does the
  math — the LLM is the explainer. It turns numbers into language. That means it
  only runs when an anomaly fires (event-driven, not every second), and it only
  generates short outputs (a paragraph, a JSON card). A 3–4B model on CPU does
  10–25 tokens/sec, which is completely acceptable for a card that appears 5–10
  seconds after an alarm. This is exactly how products like Oxmaint structure it
  too — deterministic detection, generative explanation.

  Recommended stack (all free/open source)

  - Ollama (MIT license) as the model runner — one binary, local REST API at
  localhost:11434, defaults to Q4 quantization automatically.
  - Model: Qwen3 4B or Phi-4-mini (3.8B) — the two consistently top-rated picks
  for 8GB RAM CPU inference in 2026. Both ~2.5GB on disk, ~3GB RAM at runtime,
  leaving room for your MQTT broker and Python processes. Fallback if RAM gets
  tight: Llama 3.2 3B or Qwen3 1.7B.
  - A small Python "AI analyst" service — sits next to your existing
  anomaly_detector.py, subscribes to the anomaly topic, calls Ollama, publishes
  the result to a new MQTT topic like .../ai/diagnosis. Your dashboard already
  speaks MQTT over websockets, so rendering it is just one more subscription. No
  new infrastructure.

