  2. "Ask the plant" chat panel.
  A chat box on the dashboard where the boss types "why is efficiency down?" and the LLM answers using the last N minutes of telemetry stuffed into the prompt. Small models handle this well because you're giving them all the facts — they
  just summarize.

  3. End-of-shift summary.
  One button: LLM generates a shift report — uptime, anomaly count, efficiency trend, recommended follow-ups. Bosses love auto-generated reports; it's also the cheapest feature to build.

  4. (Stretch) Manual-aware diagnosis — mini RAG.
  Drop the boiler's maintenance manual PDF into a local vector store (sqlite-vec or ChromaDB, both open source, with Ollama's free nomic-embed-text for embeddings). The incident card then cites the actual manual section: "Per manual §4.2,
  low drum level with normal feedwater indicates..." This is the feature that makes it look like a real product instead of a demo.

  The pitch framing for your boss

  Three lines that sell it:

  1. "Zero data leaves the building." The model runs air-gapped on this machine — no telemetry, no prompts, nothing goes to OpenAI/Anthropic/anyone. For industrial data that's a compliance feature, not a limitation.
  2. "Zero license cost." Ollama, Qwen/Phi, Mosquitto, scikit-learn — the entire stack is free. The only cost to scale up is hardware.
  3. "This architecture scales." Today: 4B model on a laptop explaining one boiler. Same exact code with a $1,500 GPU box: a 30B model covering the whole plant. The demo de-risks the architecture before anyone spends money.

  Practical tips so the demo doesn't embarrass you

  - Set temperature: 0.2 and force JSON output — you want consistent, boring, correct cards, not creativity.
  - Keep prompts under ~1,000 tokens — prompt processing on CPU is the slow part, more than generation.
  - Debounce: one diagnosis per anomaly event, not per message, and show a "AI analyzing…" spinner on the dashboard so latency reads as intentional.
  - Pre-pull and warm the model before the demo (ollama run qwen3:4b once) — first load from disk takes ~30s cold.
  - Close Chrome tabs during the demo — on 8GB, the browser is your real RAM competitor.

